VERTEX COORDINATES (CANONICAL EMBEDDINGS IN R^4)
=====================================================================

Tesseract {4,3,3}:
  All sign combinations of:
    (±1, ±1, ±1, ±1)

24-cell {3,4,3}:
  Even permutations of:
    (±1, ±1, 0, 0)
  Plus:
    (±1/2, ±1/2, ±1/2, ±1/2)

600-cell {3,3,5}:
  Uses golden ratio:
    φ = (1 + sqrt(5)) / 2
  Coordinate sets include:
    (0, ±1, ±φ, ±φ^-1) and cyclic permutations
  (Full list is 120 points in symmetric φ-based patterns.)

PETRIE POLYGONS
=====================================================================

Definition:
  Skew Hamiltonian cycles in the 1-skeleton of the polytope.
  Each Petrie polygon is a closed path where every consecutive
  triple of vertices forms a face, but no four consecutive do.

Use:
  Reveal hidden symmetries in orthographic projections.

STEREOGRAPHIC PROJECTION FROM S^3 TO R^3
=====================================================================

Given point (x, y, z, w) on S^3 with w != 1:

  Stereographic map:
    (x, y, z, w)  -->  ( X, Y, Z )

  Where:
    X = x / (1 - w)
    Y = y / (1 - w)
    Z = z / (1 - w)

Properties:
  - Conformal (angle-preserving)
  - Great circles on S^3 map to circles or lines in R^3

ORTHOGRAPHIC / SCHLEGEL PROJECTIONS
=====================================================================

Orthographic:
  Linear projection dropping one coordinate:
    (x, y, z, w) --> (x, y, z)

Schlegel (cell-centered):
  Project through a chosen cell to visualize adjacency
  and nesting of cells in 3D.

STRUCTURE
=====================================================================

Regular 4-polytopes:
  - Defined by {p, q, r}
  - Duals via {r, q, p}
  - Combinatorics from group actions
  - Coordinates in R^4 with high symmetry
  - Projected to R^3 via stereographic, orthographic, Schlegel
  - Petrie polygons reveal hidden adjacency cycles
